--- !u!114 &562021755
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 562021752}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 5f7201a12d95ffc409449d95f23cf332, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_FontData:
    m_Font: {fileID: 12800000, guid: 8c007fe8696d59240843ac3b71fb074c, type: 3}
    m_FontSize: 14
    m_FontStyle: 0
    m_BestFit: 0
    m_MinSize: 10
    m_MaxSize: 40
    m_Alignment: 0
    m_AlignByGeometry: 0
    m_RichText: 1
    m_HorizontalOverflow: 0
    m_VerticalOverflow: 0
    m_LineSpacing: 1
  m_Text: "<b><size=20>Europe</size></b> \U0001F30D\nEurope actively regulates the
    crypto market by developing transparent laws for investors and companies.\n\nKey
    points:\nGermany - the first country in Europe to recognize Bitcoin as a financial
    asset.\nSwitzerland (Zug) - \u201CCrypto Valley,\u201D home to many blockchain
    companies.\nEstonia - a leader in blockchain-based identification and crypto
    exchange regulation.\nFrance - regulates the crypto market through MiCA (Markets
    in Crypto-Assets Regulation).\n\nTrends and events:\nMiCA (the EU\u2019s new
    framework) regulates stablecoins and crypto exchanges.\nThe European Central
    Bank (ECB) is developing a digital euro.\nGermany and Portugal have become popular
    among crypto investors due to tax benefits.\n\U0001F539 Regulation: One of the
    most developed in the world (MiCA, AMLD5).\n\U0001F539 Mining: Limited (high
    electricity costs).\n\U0001F539 Outlook: Digital euro, asset tokenization.\n\n\U0001F30F<b><size=20>Asia</size></b>\nAsia
    is a key region for cryptocurrencies, with active development of both technology
    and regulation. It is home to major exchanges, leading mining countries, and
    pioneers in digital currencies.\n\nKey points:\nChina - banned crypto mining
    and trading, but actively develops the digital yuan (CBDC).\nJapan - one of the
    first countries to recognize Bitcoin as legal tender.\nSingapore and Hong Kong
    - crypto hubs with relatively friendly regulation.\nUAE (Dubai, Abu Dhabi) -
    a center for institutional crypto investment.\n\nTrends and events:\nBinance
    and Crypto.com chose the UAE as a key regulatory hub.\nSingapore, South Korea,
    and Japan introduced clear rules for crypto exchanges.\nIndia introduced a 30%
    tax on crypto income.\n\U0001F539 Regulation: Strict (China, India) vs. friendly
    (Singapore, UAE).\n\U0001F539 Mining: China used to be a leader, but miners relocated
    to Kazakhstan and the U.S.\n\U0001F539 Outlook: CBDC development in China, Japan,
    and India.\n\n<b><size=20>\u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043D\u0430\u044F \u0410\u043C\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043A\u0430</size></b>\nNorth
    America is a hub of crypto innovation and regulation, where the U.S., Canada,
    and El Salvador play key roles.\n\nKey points:\nUSA - the largest crypto market
    in the world, regulated by the SEC (Securities and Exchange Commission) and the
    CFTC (Commodity Futures Trading Commission).\nCanada - the first country to approve
    a Bitcoin ETF and has relatively clear crypto regulations.\nEl Salvador - the
    first country in the world to make Bitcoin legal tender.\n\nTrends and events:\nWyoming
    and Miami actively support crypto and blockchain initiatives.\nThe FBI was among
    the first to seize bitcoins from criminals (Silk Road, 2013).\nMorgan Stanley
    and JPMorgan began offering crypto products to clients.\n\U0001F539 Regulation:
    Strict (BitLicense in New York, KYC/AML requirements).\n\U0001F539 Mining: The
    U.S. became the largest hub after China\u2019s mining ban.\n\U0001F539 Outlook:
    A potential digital dollar (CBDC)."
